vadsl.AbstractBehavior; import org.apache.pekko.actor.typed.javadsl.ActorContext; import org.apache.pekko.actor.typed.javadsl.Behaviors; import org.apache.pekko.actor.typed.javadsl.Receive; With these in place we can define our first Actor, and it will say hello! Scala copy sourc\n info Pekko Actors First example A More Complex Example Introduction to Actors You are viewing the documentation for the new actor APIs, to view the Pekko Classic documentation, see Classic Actors . Module info To use Pekko Actors, add the following dependency in your project: sbt val PekkoVersion = \"2.0.0-M1\" libraryDependencies ++= Seq( \"org.apache.pekko\" %% \"pekko-actor-typed\" % PekkoVersion, \"org.apache.pekko\" %% \"pekko-actor-testkit-typed\" % PekkoVersion % Test ) Maven <properties> <scala.binary.version>2.13</scala.binary.version> </properties> <dependencyManagement> <dependencies> <dependency> <groupId>org.apache.pekko</groupId> <artifactId>pekko-bom_${scala.binary.version}</artifactId> <version>2.0.0-M1</version> <type>pom</type> <sc\nmple A More Complex Example Introduction to Actors You are viewing the documentation for the new actor APIs, to view the Pekko Classic documentation, see Classic Actors . Module info To use Pekko Actors, add the following dependency in your project: sbt val PekkoVersion = \"2.0.0-M1\" libraryDependencies ++= Seq( \"org.apache.pekko\" %% \"pekko-actor-typed\" % PekkoVersion, \"org.apache.pekko\" %% \"pekko-actor-testkit-typed\" % PekkoVersion % Test ) Maven <properties> <scala.binary.version>2.13</scala.binary.version> </properties> <dependencyManagement> <dependencies> <dependency> <groupId>org.apache.pekko</groupId> <artifactId>pekko-bom_${scala.binary.version}</artifactId> <version>2.0.0-M1</version> <type>pom</type> <scope>import</scope> </depende\n"}], "isError": false, "timestamp": 1782595124604}}
[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering system properties**\n\nI’m thinking about whether disabling unsafe exports in the environment system props is necessary. The existing build includes `--add-exports` for `sun.net.dns`, but I wonder if it’s needed for the normal scaffold. For the JDK version 25, maybe accessing `sun.net.dns` improves testing, but could we avoid it for generated tests? It seems current tests already have extra JVM arguments which might not be necessary if they don't access certain functions. I'll need to check the documentation further to clarify.\n\n**Creating JSON advisory**\n\nI’m thinking about creating a JSON advisory regarding some non-deterministic guidance for this project. It looks like I need to emphasize avoiding the removed typed actor APIs. Also, for tests that inspect DNS internals, it seems essential to have `--add-exports=java.base/sun.net.dns=ALL-UNNAMED` in place, which is already part of the existing build. It’s a bit of a tightrope walk between maintaining compatibility and ensuring we have the necessary configurations in place!\n\n**Looking into document usage**\n\nI'm trying to clarify that this isn't about \"library usage\"; it's for compiling tests instead. I'll need to check the documentation to see how to use it effectively. Maybe I should gather snippets from the pages, but I can't seem to use lynx since it's not installed. I think I'll rely on Python regex for now. I’ll also look into the automatic modules of the jar to see what options I have.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0e8f6e6aecd80a64016a403e28b3c48193b47d60418813cf8b\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqQD4zHvNVHwUGcOxfqcTkiew97BVocTy5LgeAl2tSv07vs9p83IdJg8mB0uf272gtvlM6dVPSsx-mCuwZ_zzkXGmSMv3gnmxI53G1eC7owxLIZJTTADghqZESTvkBGDrN8oFjXk-hZt1DaGwNGYaDCIZlXuL9fVq7JjyQu0E-zFggIy-QdJFkzb5QCUYu9IOQd_rfx4qxVZJmOUg3RHuV4EfQOG8OE57JVrYzLJRrvps3LgKh3g